The GitHub repository https://github.com/agroce/LOCtests contains our raw TSTL output files used for all analysis in this paper, and the exact configuration of TSTL used can be extracted by examining the first line of those files, plus version information to help with installation of appropriate versions of SUT libraries.
Note that the swarm dependency computation recently changed (https://blog.regehr.org/archives/1700), so the –noSwarmForceParent option must be used to match the older swarm results.
python-afl (https://github.com/jwilk/ python-afl) makes it possible to fuzz Python programs using AFL.
We know from past experience that python-afl can find faults that TSTL cannot (e.g., https://github.com/jmcgeheeiv/pyfakefs/issues/378).

Street Networks We retrieved the street network of the city of Boston and San Francisco and their surrounding areas from the Open Street Map (https://www.openstreetmap.org) (see Supplementary Figure 1).
The algorithm was implemented using the map matching API of Graphhoper (https://graphhopper.com/api/1/docs/map-matching/).

For each human path, the corresponding shortest distance path was calculated based on the street network from the Open Street Map (Supplementary Section 1.1) using the classic Dijkstra’s algorithm implemented in the python package of igraph-python (http://igraph.org/python/).
Figure 1c, 2A, and 3 (left) used basemap from Open Street Map (https://www.openstreetmap.org) under the Open Database License (https://www.openstreetmap.org/copyright).
Figure 3 (right) uses Map data ©2021 Google under the fair-use guidelines (https://about.google/brand-resource-center/products- and-services/geo-guidelines/ ]general-guidelines-copyright-fair-use).

b multiple methods simultaneously , c readily available for R     Animal Behaviour Pro   Animal Behaviour Pro  was developed by Nicholas Newton -Fisher  and first released in  2012    (Newton -Fisher, 2020 , https://apps.apple.com/us/app/animal -behaviour -pro/id579588319 ).

A YouTube tutorial  (“Getting Started  with Animal Behaviour Pro ” https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v9pLE9kpOnk ) is available that breaks  down the basics of the features available which is convenient for overcoming the initial learning curve ;
The Animal Observer app is initialized with the Animal Observer Toolbox  (https://fosseyfund.github.io/ AOToolBox/sidebar -left.html ).
The BORIS Android app is  designed to be  used with the BORIS  desktop software , which is available across platforms (Windows, MacOS, and Linux;  http://www.boris.unito.it/pages/download.html ).

CyberTracker   The CyberTracker software was designed by CyberTracker Conservation Organisation  and  initially released in 1997  (available at https://www.cybertracker.org/software/free -download  for all  Microsoft Windows versions) .
iOS functionality is currently in development  (https://archive.cybertracker.org/software/getting -started ).
Prim8   Prim8 mobile was developed by Monica McDonald and Scott Johnson  and initially released in  2014  (McDonald & Johnson, 2014 , http://www.prim8software.com ).

ZooMonitor   ZooMonitor was developed by Lincoln Park Zoo and was initially released in 2016 (Ross et al., 2016;  Wark et al., 2019 , https://zoomonitor.org ) to collect data that ma y impact animal welfare and inform  management decisions (Ross et al., 2016; Wark et al., 2019) .

Data availability   In our supplemental material, we provided information about the setup and the output files of each app  using foc al animal sampling of horses of the Wild Discoveries program at the University of Florida  (https://programs.ifas.ufl.edu/wild -discoveries/research -practice -materials/ accessed January 22, 2021).

We provided the setup files (ethogram and individual files) a nd the output for each application in a  Github repository (https://github.com/annemarievdmarel/behavioral -observation -data -entry -apps).
